author: {'steamid': '76561198030784015', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 11208, 'playtime_forever': 11, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 11, 'last_played': 1643878723}
review:
Griptape Backbone is more art-than-game, it's a skateboarding sandbox simulator where you can skate around, look at various "art" installations, collect cups as you skate over them, and have fun skating around a few skate park themed props if you want. 

I've seen far worse art masquerading as games on Steam, Griptape Backbone at least gets a pass on the "is it a game?" question because you do need to apply a tiny modicum of skill to collect the cups and traverse the obstacles and environments, although, being a sandbox, you're not driven to do so. Another positive point, it's not a cash grab but a sincere attempt to at least do something with Steam.  The technical implementation almost gets a pass, thanks to Unity, you've got 4K resolution support, but there's no graphics tweaks or control tweaks, so you're powerless to try improve the visual quality of the game or customise the controls to your preferences, so that's a fail. 

As for the art, well, I don't think that's very good, it's got a high-school-art-class vibe where the students don't care and slap together anything with the hopes teacher will give them a pass anyway.  It's all low poly, poorly detailed, mismatched assets that does look pretty ugly.  If you want to see art, go to an art gallery.  Likewise, the game is supposed to be "soundtrack heavy".  Spotify is basically free, you know.  I don't think the purpose a video game should be to try to compete with Spotify or my MP3 collection.  That's a competition it's going to fail at. 

This is free, which is noble, but I also don't really see the point.  If you're looking for a "fun" sandbox, you can try Goat Simulator.  If you want nice music to listen to, you know where Spotify is.  I'm not about to tell people to stop playing Apex Legends or Halo Infinite for this one.

review: This is one of those games i feel like you should only play once for the experience, or atleast that was my initial impression. I kept coming back to this "game" (I don't believe it deserves that titles as its more of an art piece), and the more I did, the more I was enthralled by the pure emotion of it. The combination of the music and the ambiance of the environment is just straight up peaceful. Although there's more that could be added or fixed, I really don't care. The jankie-ness of the structures and graphics add to the game, as if it was on purpose. The bizarre physics (or lack of) make it that more interesting. Overall a phenomenal experience. author: {'steamid': '76561198041114915', 'num_games_owned': 200, 'num_reviews': 85, 'playtime_forever': 298, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 152, 'last_played': 1598486235}
review:
This is a pretty neat little game that I would recommend for fans of vaporwave and experimental artistic games. The music, of course, really adds to the wondrous tone of the game, but the world itself is pretty cool, and the many secrets are clever and interesting. 

The only problems I see with it are the horribly janky controls and first-person perspective. I started feeling dizzy and nauseous from all the spinning and flipping. The humor might also seem a little on the nose at first because a teenager made this game, but that's just a diversion from the deeper themes you'll find if you look closer. As someone who has just recently turned 23, there was stuff to ponder and reflect on. ğŸ›¹ 6/10

author: {'steamid': '76561198018040552', 'num_games_owned': 466, 'num_reviews': 292, 'playtime_forever': 30, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 30, 'last_played': 1595198502}
review:
I have really conflicted feelings about this product and giving it a thumbs up doesn't feel entirely right, but let me explain: On the one hand, as a fan of the whole vaporwave genre, I liked or even loved most of the soundtrack and "get" the idea. The purposefully meaningless juxtaposition of postironic humour, internet memes, vague references to the obvious and not so obvious is both a fun piece of associated art and a rather fitting interactive representation of its genre. And because it fits the concept, I understand that there is no goal, no reward, and no pacing or story - but then, this piece takes it a lot further.

Meaning that the textures are not only outdated relics of an forgotten era, but also twist and melt and move and glitch and are not that easy on the eyes. Meaning that the controls are not only wonky or weird or clunky, which they are, but also borderline broken and at times completely incontrollable. Meaning that essential game mechanics, such as choosing the correct trick or skipping a song, simply don't work reliably.

The map is big enough for a feeling of exploration, also its built in a way that the same locations look different and at times interesting from another perspective - but then again, there seems to be only one secret or fun/interactive spot and with no goal other than collecting meaninglessly scattered drinks and no achievements or trading cards - both of which would've matched perfectly to a game relying on aesthetics and exploration - I felt like I had seen most of the world after ~25 minutes of gameplay and ~250/1000 collected items.

After all, this is not a bad game, I don't regret getting it for free and half and hour of gameplay is fine with me, I just think that a) this game could've been much better with a few tweaks, b) it doesn't benefit from its technical problems in any meaningful way although the theme would've been perfect for that and c) it's kinda surprising that this is the followup game, while the much more polished, interactive, entertaining and varied "Awkward Dimensions Redux" released earlier.

6/10, see it as a form of recommendation if you are a vaporwave fan and the store page looked alright to you.
developer_response: Thanks for the thoughtful review, but I never charged money for this. It's always been free, I've never sold a single game of mine ever. People have donated a few cents here and there, but it's never been a requirement or barrier of entry to my interactive trash. If you spent money, where did you buy it from?!

review:
[h1]An ethereal experience for all vaporwave sad boys out there![/h1]
Although the gameplay and controls may suck at first it's not the main focus of the game which is its overall unique aesthetic and great soundtrack featuring some of the most well known vaporwave pioneers such as Blank Banshee, Home or yung bae.
The game incorporates many different vaporwave genres such as: Seapunk, future funk, outrun, synthwave and vapormeme.
It's a lot of fun to explore the open world and find absurd easter eggs and quotes scattered around the map.
Overall I would rate the game a 7,843/10: A must play for all vaporwave enthusiasts!

review: This is a surrealist skateboarding game with cool art, enjoyable music, and memes. Controls are a bit awkward but it plays surprisingly well with a steam controller once you get the hang of it. I gave a negative review of awkward dimensions Redux due to it some of it feeling edgy and making me roll my eyes. That coming from someone who loves existentialist stuff and surrealist art. There is a bit of the "roll my eyes" bits in here (in the email section which isn't really even apart of the game). Overall, I think the existentialist themes are a bit watered down. Plus memes. The main thing here was I had fun with this, whereas I left Awkward Dimensions Redux wanting to like the game but not. It's fun, and I find myself coming back to it just chill and enjoy a simple game with cool art. Dude has more games on his website, after this I'm inclined to check them out. I really enjoyed this.

author: {'steamid': '76561198868570644', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 5, 'playtime_forever': 29, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 29, 'last_played': 1569159052}
review:
Definitely a very interesting game, but one that i think could have used a bit more work. The map is nice, and has a lot of things to skate around and explore, which would be great if it wasn't for the absolutely awful controls. Steering is almost impossible, the trick wheel sometimes doesn't work, and the brake button literally just opens a menu. The gimmick of 'you can skate on any surface', whilst it sounds cool, is actually very annoying since you tend to stick to certain objects, and i often found myself glitching out at 90 degrees to the floor after jumping of a vertical surface. There is also no save function, which is just a bit annoying, and you have to redo the tutorial EVERY SINGLE TIME you boot up the game.

The music's good, though.

review:
Beautiful game. Was a bit caught off guard by the mix of references (Camus, Harambe, Kierkegaard, and America On-line). Definitely a lot more philosophical than your usual vaporwave game.
The controls are a bit sketchy at times, but once you realize you can brake with tab, and quickly press it again to return, it turns much easier.
Quite a lot to explore, and the ending is absolutely gorgeous. Best soundtrack. Very A E S T H E T I C. Definitely recommend it. :)
developer_response: Nice noticing some of the allusions, but you still missed Jean-Paul Sartre's 'No Exit' and Myth of Sisyphus. Not to mention Waiting for Godot... ;)

author: {'steamid': '76561198043046631', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 2, 'playtime_forever': 93, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 68, 'last_played': 1566890291}
review: Honestly one of the few games that I have played recently that actually made me think. I spent a lot of the game skating around and grabbing cups, but that couldn't have been further from what I was thinking about. The little prompts and blurbs all over the game kept me thinking about my own life and where I'm going. I especially liked the angst cage, I had no reason to let them out and give myself anxiety but I did anyway and afterward felt like I was just trying to skate away from my problems. The ending hit me extremely hard after all of the introspection I did during the main portion of the game. I love this game and honestly wish I could capture the same amount of emotion that Steven did here.

author: {'steamid': '76561198255296374', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 20, 'playtime_forever': 97, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 97, 'last_played': 1547957732}
review:
i really like this game 

         in essence the game is an aesthetically pleasing skateboarding game where you search and collect plastic cups. The map is super creative with so much to explore, i have booted up the game about three times now and each time i've played it I found different parts of the map that i hadn't seen before. The game is heavily inspired by vaporwave art, therefore it is filled to the brim with quotes, jokes, and art that are well known throughout the vaporwave community. The soundtrack is also great, featuring vaporwave classics such as teenage pregnacy by blank banchee and resonance by home and a lot of other great songs that i had never heard before. As a fan of this kind of aesthetic I enjoyed all of these things very very much.

      HOWEVER while i found the skateboarding mechanics to be fun most of the times, sometimes they were glitchy and hard to control, especially at higher altitudes. Also there isn't a way to save your progress which makes completing the game very hard and tedious considering you have to collect 1000 cups to beat the game. Something that i (sadly) have not done.

     But maybe that's the way the game was intended to be played. By sitting down and exploring this wacky, weird, vaporwave world in one sitting. I don't know, maybe i'll get around to that someday. 
 
     I enjoyed this game, i recommend it, and i can't wait to see what the developer does next :)

A E S T H E T I C/ 1 0

author: {'steamid': '76561198028570547', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 2563, 'playtime_forever': 410, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 410, 'last_played': 1544396799}
review:
[h1]KOSTENLOS[/h1]

"Griptape Backbone" ist sinnfreies First-Person-Skater-Game mit Vaporwave Musik.

Das Gameplay ist mechanisch ziemlich schwach. Zwar haben wir eine Reihe von Tricks, die wir auf unserem Skateboards vollfÃ¼hren kÃ¶nnen, aber die grundlegende Steuerung an sich, die mit Maus und zwei Tasten zu bewerkstelligen ist, ist schon so trÃ¤ge und unorganisch, daÃŸ man eher den Eindruck hat, einen Panzer durch die Welt zu bewegen. Relaxt, wie das Spiel verlangt, kann ich mich bei einer solchen ungelenken Steuerung nur sehr bedingt bewegen.

Dazu spielt ein riesiger Vaporwave-Soundtrack. Wer die in den 2010ern entstandene elektronische Musikrichtung nicht kennt, dem sei gesagt, daÃŸ selbige sich vor allem den 1980ern musikalisch angenommen hat und in Retrokult-Charakter oft sehr weiche Musikabwandlungen bietet, die so vielleicht damals hÃ¤tten existieren kÃ¶nnen. Der pseudophilosophische Teppich, den sich diese nicht gerade von Intelligenz durchtrÃ¤nkte Bewegung geklÃ¶ppelt hat, wirft mit Schlagworten wie Postmoderne und Konsumkritik um sich, ohne meist zu begreifen, wovon sie eigentlich reden. 

Unsere einzige Aufgabe im Spiel nun ist es, tausend Plastikbecher einzusammeln, was an sich nicht schwierig, sondern nur zeitaufwÃ¤ndig sein dÃ¼rfte, denn es stehen tausende in der Gegend rum. 

Also fahren wir mal los. Die Welt ist  ziemlich bunt und ziemlich leer. Ãœberall finden sich irgendwelche Objekte, irgendwelche riesigen Half-Pipes oder auch nur pinke Berge. Auf denen findet man tonnenweise Memes, philosophische SprÃ¼che, unphilosophische Fragen oder auch nur irgendwelche WÃ¶rter. Wir finden eine  Figur des Sisyphos, der einen Felsen den Berg heraufzuwuchten versucht  mit dem Spruch "Making good progress today..." oder auch den Grabstein von Albert Camus. 

Das ist alles beliebig, sinnfrei, zusammenhanglos nebeinander hingestellt. Und da liegt auch der Kern des Problems. DaÃŸ der Autor meint, eine Form der postmodernen Auseinandersetzung mit dem Tod und dem Sinn des Lebens zu fÃ¼hren, ist ja gut und schÃ¶n. Leider ist er nur nicht der SouverÃ¤n Ã¼ber sein Thema. Die Zerschlagung der SinnzusammenhÃ¤nge als Wahrheit zu verkaufen ist etwa ebenso kleingeistig wie zu denken, der derridasche Dekonstruktivismus bestehe nur aus der ZerstÃ¶rung von Dingen. 

Was hier eigentlich vorhanden ist, ist ein groÃŸes Nichts, eine Ansammlung von Beliebigkeit und Plattheit. Eine stylische Auffassung von Philosophie, die sich nur noch in einer arroganten Haltung ergeht und nichts mehr mit Wahrheit zu tun hat.

Das ist bemÃ¼ht, ungekonnt, Ã¼berschÃ¤tzt, anmaÃŸend und schlichtweg strunzlangweilig und paÃŸt somit sehr gut zu dem, wofÃ¼r auch Vaporwave steht.

[h1]Wertung:[/h1]
3/10 AtmosphÃ¤re
0/10 Story
3/10 Grafik
5/10 Sound
4/10 Spielmechanik
1/10 Balancing
1/10 Spielspass

[h1]Fazit:[/h1]

author: {'steamid': '76561198056246165', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 20, 'playtime_forever': 94, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 94, 'last_played': 1539233399}
review:
This sh*t's straight dope.

:P XD
The controls feel a bit drifty, but other than that, awesome. Like a dreamy wander through my childhood. Very relaxing and casual. Love the world. I got very excited when I found the MS Paint structure with the cherry tree inside for some reason. I was like "yeah! I'm going to climb to the top of MS Paint Tower! Will this game let me do that?" ...and it did. This game functions like a playground. You just sort of monkey all over it how ever you want. No real objectives besides what you want to try next.

I wish steering was easier, I felt like I was constantly overshooting where I intended to go. And the camera does a glitchy shaking thing when you are near the edge of something while flying through the air. Could use some technical polish. But I still like this game :)

author: {'steamid': '76561198000257885', 'num_games_owned': 1314, 'num_reviews': 85, 'playtime_forever': 104, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 63, 'last_played': 1636063050}
review:
If you needa chill out, this is your game. First off the music is AMAZING; chill beats, chill hop, all good. Second the whole design is all trippy and surreal. You're really thrown into another world full of strangeness. The random quotes plastered all over the place that seemingly contradict themselves just to pull you even further away from reality are great. Then there's the skateboarding aspect which is nostolgic in a sense if you've ever been a skateboarder; 8 different tricks you'll recognize. Only gripe is the controls and camera can be a bit wonky sometimes.

Although I have not yet witnessed all this game has to offer, I keep it downloaded and explore when ever Im  feeling that lazy chill.

THE MUSIC THOUGH!

author: {'steamid': '76561198018978641', 'num_games_owned': 447, 'num_reviews': 68, 'playtime_forever': 112, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 112, 'last_played': 1530397049}
review:
This game is Vaporwave incarnate, for better and worse. The over all aesthetic is messy and lazy and often times legally dubious. Unrelated objects scatter the landscape without any sense of cohesion, fake-deep quotes are thrown in front of you everywhere you go, and all of this is to a carefully curated soundtrack of the most vaporwave-y music ever made. Holding true to vaporwave tradition, this game is highly effective at creating specific feelings with minimal effort. The ending even made me have an *emotion*, and I haven't felt one of those in 7 years.

Gameplay could be better, though. 7/10 gimme that good aesthetic daddy uwu

review:
People greenlit this?

http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails?id=813233316

Memelight. So many memes in this game. Why did Greenlight have to get horrible in its late life?

Skateboarding off of sharp edges trying to flying off of them has janky camera movement. It's like the game doesn't have any idea which surface to adhere to. Floaty and broken controls. Some cups I get out of pure luck.

At least it was free. I wouldn't pay money for this. Funny that it uses Unity because I had a smoother experience where it never dipped below 15FPS. It was between 20-30FPS.

review: A very odd and simple game with almost no particular direction except just going around the map taking in the aesthetic of what might be best described as a hallucinogenic trip to the sound of vaporwave. Otherwise, its free and easy to waste some time in to try out at least once.

author: {'steamid': '76561198090468054', 'num_games_owned': 3608, 'num_reviews': 130, 'playtime_forever': 80, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 80, 'last_played': 1511387428}
review:
Secondo prodotto (uso questo termine con una punta di provocazione) targato Steven Harmon uscito gratuitamente su questa piattaforma, Griptape Backbone Ã¨ un'altra splendida narrazione di successo di (auto-) psicoterapia esistenzialista, che richiama un diretto confronto con un simile titolo ftp, It's Always Monday. Il blog personale dell'autore Ã¨ supporto essenziale per capire cosa il gioco ci vuole narrare, e qual Ã¨ l'intima necessitÃ  alla base di questo. Il primo gioco di Harmon, Akward Dimensions Redux, era stato per l'autore una valvola di sfogo, una raccolta di idee, ansie, dubbi, progetti legati dal filo rosso dell'individuo, che con il processo creativo cercava aiuto nella comprensione di sÃ©, come se uno sguardo esterno potesse riuscire a interpretare un grumo cosÃ¬ denso e metabolizzato da sfuggire a una qualsiasi analisi dall'interno. Non sorprendentemente, Akward Dimensions non fa altro che gettare confusione. Il furore dell'interpretazione accentua il sentimento di incomprensione, e Harmon tenta cosÃ¬ di sfatare un mito autoimpostosi, ovvero il fatto che Ã¨ impossibile autorappresentarsi con il proprio lavoro. Griptape Backbone (GB) nasce da uno sforzo di distacco, di ricerca di un senso di superioritÃ  verso la propria complessitÃ , che ricade in ultima analisi in un magnifico paradosso: non c'Ã¨ niente da capire, Ã¨ tutto nelle nostre mani. GB struttura cosÃ¬ un mondo di gioco a piÃ¹ livelli, che comprendono un purgatorio digitale (il playground vaporwave principale), un'interfaccia esegetica (un menu in stile old-windows non dissimile a quelli trovati in altri progetti di diverso spessore, come Emily is Away), e, infine, la nostra stessa realtÃ , pensata come schermo conclusivo e ultimo obiettivo (se mai si possa parlare di telicitÃ  all'interno dell'intera produzione) del gioco. Un brillante post di Harmon (Vaporwave: The existentialism of the 21st century) cerca di spiegarci perchÃ© il vaporwave sia la chiave narrativa visiva e sonora di questo titolo. Vaporwave Ã¨ per l'autore la risposta, o meglio la "non-risposta", del XXI sec. alla nuova crisi del razionalismo indotta dai nuovi conflitti sovranazionali, dallo spadroneggiare dei poteri occulti, dalle pressioni del capitalismo che comprimono l'essere umano in una nuova ricerca di un valido rapporto di causalitÃ , irraggiungibile e quindi sofferto, foriero di ansie e insicurezze riguardo la vita e le scelte. Con il suo potere dissacrante, con quel senso di formattazione temporale portato della nostalgia del passato prossimo digitale, vaporwave si configura come un'immersione catartica nell'assurditÃ  del non-reale, un processo di destorificazione demartiniana che restituisce alla realtÃ  l'individuo sofferente, non dopo avergli dato gli strumenti di capire, ma dopo avergli gentilmente spiegato che, appunto, non c'Ã¨ niente da comprendere nÃ© fine ultimo da seguire. E' solo cosÃ¬ che possiamo poi intraprendere un percorso positivo di autodeterminazione, che non Ã¨ per forza attivo, forzoso, combattivo, ma anche e soprattutto contemplativo, fluttuante, armonico. La morte diventa allora uno stadio non traumatico, in quanto non Ã¨ fine di linearitÃ  progressiva, ma omogenea fase di diluizione biologica, a cui l'uomo deve pensare con serenitÃ  in tutta la sua disarmante materialitÃ . Illuminante, ironica e commovonte riesce a essere in questo senso la breve storia raccontata tramite scambio epistolare (digitale) tra Harmon e la segreteria d'ammissione a una scuola di specializzazione, in cui tutta la filosofia del self-made man anglosassone viene rigirata come un calzino dall'autore, che si bea delle incomprensioni generate da prospettive opposte e incompatibili. Girovagando per il grande playground, il giocatore realizza a un certo punto che GB propone un unico obiettivo, risultante nel collezionare un gran numero di token sparsi in quantitÃ  su ogni superficie navigabile. Il reward finale viene descritto come l'accesso a una grande veritÃ , che, se il giocatore Ã¨ stato vigile nella peregrinazione digitale, si anticipa facilmente in una non-risposta. E' per questo che ho apprezzato moltissimo il momento in cui ho constatato che GB non si limita alla piÃ¹ che facile e a portata di mano soluzione di far terminare il tutto d'improvviso, senza nessuna indicazione esplicita, o semplicemente di far continuare l'attivitÃ  di raccolta puntando sull'immagine di un finto traguardo. In GB il finale c'Ã¨, ed Ã¨ un momento di ascensione che, se da una parte stringe l'occhio molto esplicitamente all'immaginario di Proteus, risulta originalissimo in quanto totalmente centrato sulla singolaritÃ  dell'individuo creativo. E' tramite un tunnel cosparso di foto e filmati dell'infanzia di Harmon che il giocatore puÃ² ricongiungersi alla storia, alla dimensione del reale, trascinato dalla spinta calda dei ricordi e delle persone che ci hanno segnato. La trovata Ã¨ inoltre di grande valenza retroattiva, visto che spiega in extremis il simbolo stesso dello skateboard, e quello strano intro live-action in cui i comandi essenziali vengono abbozzati. Harmon vede nello skateboard un simbolo di mobilitÃ , di transitorietÃ , di evoluzione, che perÃ² non ha niente a che vedere con una tecnologia piÃ¹ o meno avanzata, con un punto preciso nel tempo, con una valenza etica o con un principio di qualitÃ  commerciale. Lo skateboard Ã¨ un mezzo di trasporto rudimentale nelle meccaniche psicologiche dell'io, in quanto si colloca spazialmente sul retro di un garage di casa, e ha bisogno di una spinta personale, un volontÃ  unica, per raggiungere una destinazione che puÃ² essere letteralmente individuabile in qualsiasi dimensione proposta, o in nessuna di essa.
Per concludere, GB Ã¨ esempio di come il videogioco possa essere contemporaneamente processo di purificazione solipsistico e altruista guida interpretativa della realtÃ . Il suo messaggio, cosÃ¬ sospeso e indeterminato, Ã¨ reso con grande tensione espressiva in termini strettamente attuali, usando una corrente di effimera valenza quotidiana. Ma va bene cosÃ¬: prospettiva e retrospettiva sono in realtÃ  molto simili tra loro, e il loro intersecarsi serve a forgiare il nostro senso di esistenza, che inizia e finisce con noi soli.

review: Having enjoyed Awkward Dimensions I was super down to play this game. My major gripe is that it controls awful. author: {'steamid': '76561198337608180', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 7, 'playtime_forever': 176, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 118, 'last_played': 1665267586}
review: Very few people have the skill to do this with games. Somehow you are able to turn such a simple concept into such intresting and very fun gameplay! The added bonus of the music and homescreen menu of windows 94 make the game just that better! I also love the quirky 80's and 90's theme in the game, The random yet very fun obstacles were fun to skate around, games like this is what I live for! I also love the soundtrack of the game and the fact I can choose both the song I want to play and the volume I want is just so convenient yet again you create a fun game I hope to see what you have in store in the future :)

author: {'steamid': '76561198066392472', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 2, 'playtime_forever': 99, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 99, 'last_played': 1500088158}
review:
tl;dr: In concept, this game is great. In execution, it's frustrating and a boring. Would not reccomend.

I was very excited to play this game-- the graphical style and atmosphere, the skateboarding gameplay, the fact that it seemed to be one of those very rare games built completely around movement-- it seemed like the perfect thing to tie me over until Perfect Stride came out, a similar game which has been in development for a few years now. It looked to me that this game had even been inspired by Perfect Stride, which was a very good sign, as the PS alpha is probably the best game I've ever played.
However, Griptape Backbone fell short of my expectations on a lot of levels. The gameplay, the music, the graphics, and the story, are all close to being good, but all of them fall short, and come together to make a frustrating and not very fun experience. I'll go over each and explain why they don't satisfy me.
First and foremost, the gameplay. This is the most obvious problem in the game-- It's kinda a mess. As I said before, this is one of those games that is completely movement focused, which is a rare thing. Most other games have something else thrown into the mix, even the ones you would consider mostly being about moving. Most platformers have enemies to dodge instead of just moving from place to place, and most skateboarding games are more about tricks and comboes than the movement. But the few games that do build themselves off movement are some of the most satisfying out there-- Super Meat Boy, Mirror's Edge, and the aforementioned Perfect Stride. The appeal in these games is how satisfying it is to just get from one place to another, because the motions are just so fluid and weighted-- it feels like you're controlling something real and tangible. Now, it's often said that t he quickest way to ruin a game is by giving it bad controls, and needless to say, this is even more true for a game in which movement is the primary form of gameplay. But in Griptape Backbone, the controls not just unpolished, but completely a mess. Even after playing through the game and beating it, I still don't understand the movement system very well. It seems simple enough, you left click to propel yourself forwards, right click and flick the mouse to do tricks, and move the mouse to turn. The first issue is that the turning is super frustrating to deal with-- it feels like you have to spam click the mouse to get your trajectory to properly change, and even when you do that, sometimes it doesn't turn with the responsivity you want it to. It might(?) hame something to do with how fast you were already moving, but honestly, that's entirely a guess, because this is completely beyond me. The other issue is that there is no way to slow yourself down. The only thing like that you can do is to completely brake (which, might I add, can only be done by opening the pause menu?), so you don't have the option to finetune your speed. Now, you might think you could just click  a specific number of times to get the right speed, but that's not really an option, because it feels like there's a delay before the speed boost applies, so that can only really work if you have a lot of patience and a giant runway leading up to every trick you wanna pull off. The game is also really glitchy at times-- sometimes, the game just takes you and puts your gravity pointing in really weird directions while mid-jump, and I got stuck in a wall and spent a long while just trying to get myself out. I didn't really want to restart the game, as I had made a lot of progress, and the developer neglected to put a save feature into his game. Even after playing through the whole game, the controls jujst never felt right. They were to slidy and unpredictable, which is the primary downfall of this game.
Next up, the graphics/visual presentation. The game is based off of the Vaporwave visual style, or as this game's developer likes to call it, "A E S T H E T I C." Again, on paper, a great thing to base the visuals off of, and at first, it's kinda great. You come into the game and are greeted with things like a giant purple grid mountain and the Windows Solitaire bouncing cards. It's just a great sign that someone a bit more seasoned could make a really dazzling game like this, but again, this falls short under scrutiny, or just under a casual playthrough of the game. Many of the textures have some sort of shader or effect applied which makes them warp and shift around, which is somewhat disorienting and doesn't add anything to the visuals. There's also a shader which makes certain objects seem pixellated, but that just... doesn't look good, doesn't look thematically relevant, and is just detrimental to the whole feel. The other, major problem about this, is that the developer seems not to actually care that much about Vaporwave, but is instead someone who kinda jumped in saying "Hey, Vaporwave is cool, how about I try and use it to make somehing hip and trendy, and just grasp onto one or two things about the style from the surface level and just use those repeatedly?" The most prime example of this is the extreme overuse of the word "aesthetic." He seems to use it any chance he gets, and since it's such a minor part of the Vaporwave scene, but such a major part of the Vaporwave memes, it seems like he doesn't really understand what makes Vaporwave what it is. He also seems to miss anything the whole consumerism point inherent to Vaporwave, which is one of its main defining characteristics. It seems like he's just some kid born in the mid 90s who latched onto the old technology aspect of Vaporwave because he thinks it's nostalgic without really understanding the deeper point. It just seems like he's trying to force his way into it, which is very much against the point and kinda undermines the presentation.
The music is Vaporwave. Wow, who woulda thought. It's fitting considering everything else, but I personally think faster, more intense tracks with a bit more feel that you can really get into help this type of game a lot, but that is just my personal opinion. There is nothing wrong with the soundtrack, I just think that it could be better.
The story is hinted at, but I feel like depending on what you're expecting, it's either way too ovbious, or not obvious at all. Spoilers ahead, I guess, but this isn't really a very plot based game. So at the beginning of the game, the loading screen implies that you are in a hospital, very nearly dead, and that the realm in which the game takes place is purgatory. The primary issue with this is that if you're not expecting a story, it would likely just seem like gibberish to you, but if you are expecting a story, it is way too obvious and literally spoiled by the loading screen before the game even starts. Not only that, but there are no further hints after that furthering it (or if there are any, they are very, very well hidden)-- so the game either expects you to figure out its story solely before playing it, or not figure anything out at all. I don't think this is  an optimal storytelling method. The only other time the story comes in is the ending, where, if you somehow managed to be patient enough to collect 1000 aesthetics (a name which doesn't fit very well, as you're collecting cups-- again, it seems like he's just trying to throw as many buzzwords in there to make this seem on the surface level like Vaporwave) then a giant temple appears in the middle of the game area. If you go to the temple, you are levitated up to the sky, and then you get to watch a slideshow of the developers life, along with his home videos from his childhood, while he voices over about how he's been enlightened, and then finally dies. I get that it's supposed to be him reflecting on his whole life at the very end, but like the rest of this game, okay idea in practice, executed really poorly. The slideshow and videos go on for way too long, and it's just boring. (abrupt end,hit character lmt)

author: {'steamid': '76561198161396032', 'num_games_owned': 227, 'num_reviews': 32, 'playtime_forever': 24, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 24, 'last_played': 1496692092}
review:
I have a lot of positive feedback and constructive critism to put out:
- The idea of an openworld, aimlessly roaming, "screw the laws of physics" skateboarding game is probably the most innovative preposition I've seen on Steam all year.
- Without the presence of quests, it's so easy and comforting for my autistic ass to get lost in the game without being conscious of objectives breathing down my neck.
- The whole purgatory realm combined with the hospital atmosphere during loading makes death seem a lot less scary. The inclusion of the programs in the menu give the main character a completely relatable backstory and also sends a message about how you cannot run away from your problems forever.

My constructive critism, while also being aware that programming is difficult and I personally cannot program or mod to save my life:
- The controls and visuals are clunky and could use some work. I spent about five minutes skating around the outside of a tube because I could not figure out how to get onto the ground again; the camera kept shaking so I could not focus on any particular target.
- I found the navigation difficult to get used to, but I also understand that using the mouse would be easier for others. I've never successfully ridden a skateboard so I cannot imagine if the controls in the game are similar to what skateboarding feels like in real life. My suggestion would be to give players the option to use the classic WASD keys to navigate or the mouse, as was the game's initial intention (and the ability to switch between the controls)
- I would definitely donate to the developers of this game so that they can improve our experience (TM). I'd rather give my money to people who work hard on stuff like this!

A personal message to the devs:
PLEASE DO NOT STOP! Creation and innovation is important today in regards to the gaming culture. As someone who needs to relieve a lot of stress all the time forever, this can really help a lot of people cool off and wind down. Thank you!

author: {'steamid': '76561198028399245', 'num_games_owned': 491, 'num_reviews': 20, 'playtime_forever': 109, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 109, 'last_played': 1495817499}
review:
A free game all about existentialism and aesthetics? Hell yeah! 

A skateboarding game where you see only your skateboard move, and must collect aesthetic cups to achieve enlightenment, is one of the finest examples of what vaporwave and aesthetics are. If you're ever curious as to what vaporwave is, or what aesthetics are, play this game. There's also an underlying narrative that I think I understand, but won't mention due to it being rather interesting and fun to take in as you play. 

However, the skateboard is incredibly hard to control, and the camera jerks around a lot due to being able to essentially skate on any surface. But that doesn't really matter in the end, because there are so many of those cups you can collect that missing a ton doesn't cause any problems. And anyways, what is there to really complain about when you have vaporwave playing in the background as you ride a floppy disk ramp to get into a drawing from MS Paint.

10/10.

author: {'steamid': '76561198080208738', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 157, 'playtime_forever': 31, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 31, 'last_played': 1495593255}
review:
Okay. You know how you review the game you just played, explain what made it great, how you enjoyed it, etc...
What if I reviewed the developer instead.

There is something, at least to me, more than just this game. It seems silly, but there is an underlying innocence and, honestly for me, jealousy on my end.

[b]Steven Harmon[/b]
Indie Developer, Game Dabbler, Composer, Teenager.

His first game had more structure than this, and was in fact more interesting. 
THIS game was for sure an interesting experience, and it was very funny actually. 
But I think the story is broader. Steven is an early developer, but the passion and the uniqueness just seeps through his work, its like he's famous yet completely unknown. To be frank, you should be expecting more from him and expecting a journey. This journey is games made by a guy who tries to be himself by expressing himself and finding himself through what seem to be amateur unity games... and yet it is so clear. 

I don't even care about the games anymore. This man fascinates me. He intrigues me.

Its almost if a version of myself went off and decided to TRY. That version left my other half, who writes reviews about a reflection in the mirror that I wish I could be. These games invoke a self-journey through someone elses journey.

And since I assume Steven will be reading this, this is a direct message to you:

Don't stop evolving. If someone, anyone, is applauding you, you need to make them throw fucking ROSES at you the next time. You are young. You are ambitious. This is the start of something amazing and you know it.

Don't take this opportunity for granted. 

I will follow your work. You don't have to care that I care but I will be there at your award ceremony when the world cheers your name and your portfolio is thick, and your changes are made. This is no longer for fun, this is for your humanity. This for others humanities. You have so much power now. You are doing great things. Now slam dunk some more content onto my platter.  

Thank you.

I rate the game a 7/10 it was buggy but the aesthetic was amazing.
I rate the developer... well... no numbers can really describe it.

author: {'steamid': '76561198286773301', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 4, 'playtime_forever': 134, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 30, 'last_played': 1542677076}
review:
level design: 11/10

music: phire/10

controls: 5/10
felt like driving a container ship on lean.

Steve ol' boy, love your style. came here after playing awkward demension redux. it's never about the actual gameplay it's about the art and the feels. games need more phylisophical pointlessness nowadays. 

only thing i didnt like were the controls. turning was more of a suggestion rather than an actual control, which made it tough to do the line rides you want. and the gravity is awkward. the wall-riding code made your freefall gravitate toward whatever angle surface you were close to, which would cause mid-air seizures sometimes. but none of these made it unplayable.
Definitely recommend this game, i mean.. its free, just download and soak in the experience ya dingus.

Steve (or anyone really), if you read this, i highly recommend listening to some Allen Watts talks if you havent already. really helps with that soul crushing existential meaningless in life.
cheers.

author: {'steamid': '76561198288577396', 'num_games_owned': 112, 'num_reviews': 11, 'playtime_forever': 1777, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 387, 'last_played': 1572827484}
review:
I really don't know what to say about this game; it's hilarious whilst having a serious undertone, it made me think whilst simultaneously allowing me to be submerged into it, it's bittersweet and deep and a whole bunch of other adjectives I cannot conceive at the moment. A beautiful collusion of opposites.

Basically you're playing as a skater in purgatory and you need to collect 1000 aesthetics (paper cups) to reach enlightenment. Along the way, you get to enjoy some /music plays/ memes and a top-notch soundtrack. 

Would recommend highly to anyone who likes fun and deep philosophical questions.
My only complaint is that you can't choose "pass butter" as a reason for purpose.

[i]Griptape Backbone[/i] is a game that appears to be about skateboarding, but is actually about much more. The main focuses are about death and the state of the modern artistic pursuit. Akin to Steven Harmon's other games, this piece focuses on having the player contemplate the deeper philosophical ideas in the game.

author: {'steamid': '76561198093124113', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 27, 'playtime_forever': 26, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 26, 'last_played': 1494243103}
review:
I appreciate what this game is going for. Vaporwave's aesthetic is something I still love in any medium, whether it was intentional or not. A game with Vaporwave aesthetics, both in sound and visuals, should be a cool, fun time.

Vaporwave deserves a better game than this. Moving around in the skateboard sucks if you're trying to collect all the cups, and if you're not, it's hard to find a place where you can just chill and float without encountering something that makes the camera jitter a bunch. It's a cool looking world, but I don't understand why a skateboard was chosen to explore it, especially one that controls as awkwardly as this one.

Also, when I crashed into the statue of Sisyphus, the game made a horrifically loud sound, one way louder than the music or any other sound effects or the volume I had on my PC.

The music's great, the visuals are great, the weird pause screen OS is great, the memes written on the building walls are kinda bad but I can deal with them, I just wish it was all in a game that was actually fun to play. The only reason I would recommend this game is because it is free, that would be the case for any other price.

author: {'steamid': '76561198067202125', 'num_games_owned': 2046, 'num_reviews': 14, 'playtime_forever': 17, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 17, 'last_played': 1494051794}
review:
I feel awful writing a negative review about this game, but it's just overall an unpleasant experience.

Controls are absolutely horrendous. Moving anywhere feels like iceskating on a bannana peel. With conventional controls, this could be recoverable, but the mouse steering makes it a real struggled to aim anywhere at all.

Partially due to the controls, I ended up with pretty severe motion sickness from this. The jittering combined with poor controls, and the overall nature of the game's style makes it unpleasant. I don't normally get motion sick, but this was definitely an horrendous experience.

There's not too much else to say about the game. The soundtrack is pretty nice if you're into the genre, and the vaporwave aesthetics can be pleasant in places. The world design is a redeeming feature, and the level is fun to explore. It's unique, but also repetitive at the same time. It's difficult to properly enjoy the world with the bad controls though.

There isn't much of a story to the game from what I can tell. It's a shame, since Awkward Dimensions Redux had a pretty amazing story experience and this game just lacks that. I really wish that I could recommend this game. But I can't.
